6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates hourly using oracle prices and open interest imbalances, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.01% per hour. Phemex uses traditional 8-hour funding intervals based on premium/discount to spot index, creating larger but less frequent rate adjustments. GMX's hourly settlements provide more granular arbitrage opportunities but require active monitoring. Phemex's longer intervals allow for position planning but can result in higher accumulated funding costs during trending markets."}]]}]
7:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"GMX's hourly funding settlements create more frequent arbitrage windows, while Phemex's 8-hour intervals offer larger rate movements. GMX suits active traders willing to pay higher fees, while Phemex favors volume-based strategies with lower costs."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculation methods differ between GMX and Phemex?","answer":"GMX uses oracle-based pricing with GLP liquidity pool dynamics affecting rates, while Phemex employs traditional mark price methodology against spot index. GMX rates reflect on-chain liquidity conditions, whereas Phemex follows conventional perpetual funding mechanics."},{"question":"What are the main risks when arbitraging between these platforms?","answer":"GMX carries oracle manipulation and smart contract risks inherent to DeFi protocols, plus higher transaction costs. Phemex presents counterparty risk and potential withdrawal delays during high volatility, along with possible liquidity constraints on smaller altcoin pairs."},{"question":"Which platform is more suitable for institutional funding rate strategies?","answer":"Phemex's 0.01% maker fees and established CEX infrastructure make it more suitable for institutional volume strategies. GMX appeals to DeFi-native institutions seeking on-chain exposure, but higher costs limit large-scale arbitrage profitability."}]}]
